## 🔁 Example: Polling Every 2 Minutes (Saga style)

```js
import { call, delay, put } from 'redux-saga/effects'

function* pollSaga() {
  while (true) {
    const data = yield call(fetchApi)
    yield put({ type: 'UPDATE_DATA', payload: data })
    yield delay(120000) // 2 minutes
  }
}
```

✅ Very clean  
✅ Impossible to do this cleanly with thunks

***

## 🧪 Testing Advantage (Big Reason to Use Saga)

Saga functions are **easy to test**:

```js
const saga = fetchUsersSaga()

expect(saga.next().value).toEqual(call(fetchUsersApi))
expect(saga.next(users).value).toEqual(
  put({ type: 'FETCH_USERS_SUCCESS', payload: users })
)
```

✅ No mocking promises  
✅ Deterministic behavior

***

## ❓ Redux Saga vs Redux Thunk

| Feature        | Saga        | Thunk         |
| -------------- | ----------- | ------------- |
| Syntax         | Generators  | Functions     |
| Async flows    | ✅ Complex   | ❌ Simple only |
| Cancellation   | ✅ Easy      | ❌ Hard        |
| Testability    | ✅ Excellent | ❌ Moderate    |
| Learning curve | ❌ Higher    | ✅ Lower       |

✅ **Thunk** → small apps  
✅ **Saga** → enterprise / complex apps

***

## ⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ Saga logic inside reducer  
❌ Side effects in reducers  
❌ Overusing Saga for simple async  
❌ Forgetting to run rootSaga

✅ Reducer = pure  
✅ Saga = side effects

***

## 🧠 When Should You Use Redux Saga?

✅ Large enterprise application  
✅ Complex async workflows  
✅ Authentication & permissions  
✅ Background tasks  
✅ Need cancellation / retry / polling

❌ Not recommended for small apps

***

## ✅ Perfect Interview Answer (One‑Liner)

> **Redux Saga is a Redux middleware that uses generator functions to handle complex asynchronous side effects like API calls, polling, and background tasks in a predictable, testable way outside of React components and reducers.**

